HEADWORD: Monomorphous
<hw>Mon`o*mor"phous</hw>
<pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + Gr.
<grk>morfh`</grk> form.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Having but a
single form; retaining the same form throughout the various stages of
development; of the same or of an essentially similar type of structure;
-- opposed to <contr>dimorphic</contr>, <contr>trimorphic</contr>, and
<contr>polymorphic</contr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monomphalus</ent>⟦br⟧
